1. Autoboxing:
Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive type into its corresponding wrapper class object.

Example: Converting int to Integer.
Why it happens: 
This usually occurs when you pass a primitive to a method that expects an object (like adding an int to an ArrayList<Integer>).
Java// Logic: primitive -> object


int num = 10;
Integer obj = num; // Autoboxing


2. Unboxing:
Unboxing is the reverse—the automatic conversion of a wrapper class object into its corresponding primitive type.

Example: Converting Integer to int.
Why it happens:
This occurs when you try to use a wrapper object in an arithmetic operation or assign it to a primitive variable.
Java// Logic: object -> primitive


Integer obj = new Integer(20);
int num = obj; // Unboxing

ProcessDirectionExample
Autoboxing          primitive → Wrapper Integer   val = 5;
Unboxing            Wrapper → primitive int     n = val;
